      <h1>R/evolve</h1>
      <p>At the Musashino Art University Electronic Music Society, I was responsible for the complete design and construction of venues and spatial installations. My first project was a projection wall measuring 3 meters in height and 10 meters in width. From there, I developed increasingly experimental environments, including a special stage enclosed by three giant circular screens, eventually leading to the design and construction of a massive curved screen measuring 4 meters by 20 meters.</p>
      <p>Through modular design strategies, the pursuit of efficient construction methods, and the physical process of fabricating wooden structures by hand, each iteration became an increasingly in-depth experiment in creating new spatial experiences.</p>
      <p>Rather than presenting performances from a single frontal direction, these spaces were designed to be experienced from all 360 degrees. By placing the stage at the center of the venue, performers, audiences, visuals, and sound continuously responded to one another, producing an environment in which all elements gradually merged into a unified whole.</p>
      <p>The entire space was organized around the structure of “rotation,” with the central stage acting as its axis. As viewers moved through the environment and their perspectives shifted, the relationships between image, light, and sound transformed continuously, allowing the venue itself to function as a total experiential apparatus.</p>
      <p>The screen existed as a “window” separating landscapes represented through RGB from the physical world itself.</p>
      <p>Today, we live surrounded not only by sunlight, but also by electronically reproduced RGB light emitted from displays, LEDs, and projections. Regardless of age or background, much of our perception and experience of landscape is already mediated through artificial light.</p>
      <p>Photo: Rei Sato / Taishi Tani
      <p>“Architecture of Light” is an attempt to reconsider architecture not as something constructed solely through physical materials, but as spaces and landscapes composed through electronic light itself.</p>


